{{Orphan|date=July 2014}}
The '''Professional-Managerial class''' was an influential [[New Class]] hypothesis in [[social science]] in the United States in the 1970s by John and [[Barbara Ehrenreich]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Ehrenreich|first=John| title=Between Labor and Capital|year=1979|publisher=South End Press|location=Boston|isbn=0-89608-037-4|edition=1st|author2=Barbara Ehrenreich |editor=Pat Walker}}</ref> The Ehrenreichs hypothesized a [[social class]] within [[capitalism]] that, by controlling production processes through superior management skills, was neither [[proletarian]] nor [[bourgeois]]. This hypothesis contributed to the [[Marxist]] debates on class in [[Fordism]] and was used as an analytical category in the examination of non-proletarian employees.
This group of [[middle class]] professionals is distinguished from other social classes by their training and education, typically business qualifications and university degrees,<ref>{{cite web|last=Philip|first=Green|title=Retrieving Democracy: In Search of Civic Equality|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/middle-class#cite_note-25|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield}}</ref> with occupations including [[academics]], [[teachers]], [[social workers]], [[engineers]], [[managers]], [[nurses]], and middle-level [[Administrator (business)|administrators]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kellner|first=Hansfried|title=Hidden Technocrats: The New Class and New Capitalism|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/middle-class#cite_note-26|publisher=Transaction Publishers|author2=Frank W. Heuberger |year=1994}}</ref> The professional-managerial class tends to have incomes above the average for their country.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gail|first=Kelly|title=Women's higher education in comparative perspective|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V-CKcuRAu8EC&pg=PA254&dq=Professional+Managerial+Class+salary&q=Professional+Managerial+Class+salary&hl=en#v=snippet&q=Professional%20Managerial%20Class%20salary&f=false|publisher=Springer|author2=Sheila Slaughter |year=1990}}</ref>
It is estimated that in the [[United States]] during 1930, people in professional-managerial class occupations made up less than 1 percent of total employment. In 1972, about 24 percent of American jobs were in professional-managerial class occupations. By 1983 the number had risen to 28 percent and in 2006, 35 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ehrenreich|first=Barbara|title=Barbara and John Ehrenreich: The Real Story Behind the Crash and Burn of America's Managerial Class|url=http://www.alternet.org/economy/barbara-and-john-ehrenreich-real-story-behind-crash-and-burn-americas-managerial-class?page=0%2C0|work=AlterNet|accessdate=18 November 2013|author2=John Ehrenreich |date=February 2013}}</ref>
